    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-07T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-07T05:00:00-05:00" n="271"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d271">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4044: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="#p_CES1"
                            type="from">Cunningham</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-07T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 7, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 7—2:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>12. I have just been assured by Consul General <persName corresp="#p_MK1"
                        >Murai</persName> that the military force arriving today would not be landed
                    in the International Settlement. That it is the intention to land at Woosung and
                    he believed they had already landed at 5 o’clock. Refer to this office’s
                    telegram No. 8 of February 6th, 5 p.m. Repeated to the Legation, Nanking and
                    Tokyo for information.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CES1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
